1 How is the distribution of nationalities related to current economic status?

In Switzerland, it is common to have part-time employment contracts of 80% or sometimes even 60%. For foreign nationals, this situation may seem unusual. Therefore, one of the hypotheses we investigated is that foreign nationals might work more hours than local residents.

1.1 Preparation to work

Loading Libraries, Functions, and Decoding Info

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
source("chart_functions.R")
source("decode_lists.R")

Loadind data zp_merged_data.csv (presumably contains data about people). hh_merged_data.csv (household-related data).

zp_merged_data <- read.csv("zp_merged_data.csv")
hh_merged_data <- read.csv("hh_merged_data.csv")

Merging the Datasets

# ' 
merged_data <- hh_merged_data %>%
  left_join(zp_merged_data, by = c("HOUSEHOLDYEARLYID"="HOUSEHOLDYEARLYID","YEAR_QUIZ"="YEAR_QUIZ"))

Selecting Variables for Chart Building

selected_data <- merged_data %>% select(RENTNET,NATIONALITYCAT,TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM, 
                          RESIDENTPERMIT,CURROCCUPATIONISCOAGG,YEAR_QUIZ)

Filtering Extreme High RENTNET Values

selected_data <- selected_data %>% filter(RENTNET<5000)

Decoding Numeric Data

selected_data <- decode(selected_data, TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM, for_numeric_variables)
selected_data$TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM <- as.numeric(as.character(selected_data$TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM))
selected_data <- decode(selected_data, RENTNET, for_numeric_variables)
selected_data$RENTNET <- as.numeric(as.character(selected_data$RENTNET))

Decoding Categorical Data

selected_data <- decode(selected_data, CURROCCUPATIONISCOAGG, occupation_isco_agg)
selected_data <- decode(selected_data, NATIONALITYCAT, nationality_category)
selected_data <- decode(selected_data, RESIDENTPERMIT, permit)

1.2 Exploring Variable Distributions

selected_data %>% filter(!is.na(NATIONALITYCAT)) %>% 
  distribution_numeric(TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM, "Work time per week")

selected_data %>% filter(!is.na(NATIONALITYCAT)) %>% 
  distribution_numeric(RENTNET, "Rent Price")

1.2.1 Work Time per Week Distribution

Observation:
- Foreign nationals show a strong peak around 40 hours per week, indicating a more standardized schedule. - Swiss residents also peak at 40 hours but have a flatter distribution, indicating higher variability.

1.2.2 Rent Distribution (Foreign vs.Swiss)

Observation:
- Both groups have similar rent peaks (~1,500 CHF).
- The rent distribution for foreign nationals is more concentrated in the lower rent range.

distribution_categorical(selected_data, CURROCCUPATIONISCOAGG, "Ocupation")

distribution_categorical(selected_data, NATIONALITYCAT, "Nationality")

distribution_categorical(selected_data, RESIDENTPERMIT, "Permit")

1.2.3 Occupation Distribution

Observation:
- A substantial portion of the data is missing or unreported (NA).
- Among the reported data, academic and service/sales jobs are the most common.
- Managerial and armed forces roles show minimal representation.

1.2.4 Nationality Distribution

Observation:
- Swiss residents form the majority of the dataset. - Foreign nationals make up a smaller proportion overall.

1.2.5 Resident Permit Distribution

Observation:
- Most foreign nationals hold a Permit C (long-term residency), followed by Permit B (short-term residency). - Other permit types are relatively negligible in the dataset.

1.3 Analysis of Working Hours

General overwiev Worktime between Swiss and forein peopele

summary_stats <- selected_data %>%
  group_by(NATIONALITYCAT) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_hours = mean(TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_hours = median(TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_hours = sd(TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM, na.rm = TRUE),
    min_hours = min(TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM, na.rm = TRUE),
    max_hours = max(TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM, na.rm = TRUE),
    Q1 = quantile(TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM, probs = 0.25, na.rm = TRUE),
    Q3 = quantile(TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM, probs = 0.75, na.rm = TRUE),
    count = n()
  )

selected_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM) & !is.na(NATIONALITYCAT)) %>% 
  group_by(NATIONALITYCAT) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = NATIONALITYCAT, y = TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM, fill = NATIONALITYCAT)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(
    fun = median,
    geom = "text",  
    aes(label = round(..y.., 1)),  
    vjust = 0.5,
    hjust = 6.5,
    color = "black",  
    size = 4
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Comparison of Working Hours by Nationality",
    x = "Nationality",
    y = "Weekly Working Hours"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

print(summary_stats)

1.3.1 Median Weekly Working Hours

  • Migrants (Foreign): Median weekly working time is 41 hours.
  • Swiss Residents: Median weekly working time is 40 hours.
  • Implication:
    • This small difference aligns with the hypothesis that migrants might work slightly more on average to meet economic demands.

1.3.2 Mean Weekly Working Hours

  • Migrants (Foreign): Average working hours is 37.85.
  • Swiss Residents: Average working hours is 35.61.
  • Implication:
    • This supports the idea that migrants tend to work longer hours overall, potentially reflecting the economic disparity between the groups.

1.3.3 Spread and Variability

  • Standard Deviation:
    • Migrants: 10.76, indicating more consistent working schedules.
    • Swiss Residents: 12.63, showing greater variability in working hours.
  • First Quartile (Q1):
    • Migrants: 38 hours, reflecting a larger proportion working full-time or near full-time hours.
    • Swiss Residents: 29 hours, suggesting more part-time or flexible schedules among locals.

1.4 Rent Analysis from a Financial Perspective

rent_analysis <- selected_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(NATIONALITYCAT)) %>%
  mutate(
    pays_rent = case_when(
      RENTNET > 0 ~ "Pays Rent",
      RENTNET < 1 | is.na(RENTNET) ~ "Does Not Pay Rent"
    )
  ) %>%
  group_by(NATIONALITYCAT, pays_rent) %>%
  summarise(count = n(), .groups = "drop") %>% #  .groups = "drop",    
  group_by(NATIONALITYCAT) %>% #    NATIONALITYCAT    
  mutate(percentage = round(count / sum(count) * 100,2)) %>%
  ungroup() #   ,     

ggplot(rent_analysis, aes(x = pays_rent, y = percentage, fill = NATIONALITYCAT)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  geom_text(
    aes(label = round(percentage, 2)),
    position = position_dodge(width = 0.9),
    vjust = -0.5,                     #    
    size = 3
  ) +
  labs(title = "     ",
       x = " ",
       y = "",
       fill = "  ") +
  theme_minimal()

print(rent_analysis)

1.4.1 Rent Payment Proportion

  • Migrants (Foreign):
    • 73.9% pay rent.
    • 26.1% do not pay rent.
  • Swiss Residents:
    • 44% pay rent.
    • 56% do not pay rent.

1.4.2 Comparison Between Groups

  • A significantly higher percentage of migrants pay rent compared to Swiss residents (73.9% vs.44%).
  • Swiss residents are more likely not to pay rent (56%), which might indicate higher rates of home ownership or alternative living arrangements among locals.

1.5 Analysis Work Time by Permit

mean_by_permit <- selected_data %>% filter(TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM>0) %>% 
  select(RESIDENTPERMIT, TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM) %>% 
  group_by(RESIDENTPERMIT) %>% 
  summarise(mean_time = round(mean(TIMEWORKEDPERWEEKSUM, na.rm = TRUE, trim = 0.1), 2), .groups = "drop") %>% 
  filter(!is.na(RESIDENTPERMIT)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(mean_time))

ggplot(mean_by_permit, aes(x = reorder(RESIDENTPERMIT, -mean_time), y = mean_time, fill = RESIDENTPERMIT)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  geom_text(
    aes(label = round(mean_time, 1)),  #    
    vjust = -0.5,                     #    
    size = 3
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Mean work time per week by permit",
    x = "Permit type",
    y = "Mean work time per week"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  guides(fill = "none")

print(mean_by_permit)
## # A tibble: 7  2
##   RESIDENTPERMIT mean_time
##   <chr>              <dbl>
## 1 Permit L            41.2
## 2 Permit B            39.8
## 3 Permit C            39.0
## 4 Swiss               36.8
## 5 Permit F            34.7
## 6 Permit Ci           34.0
## 7 Permit N            32.1

Interpretation: Since Permit B and C holders represent the majority of foreign nationals, we compare them to local residents. The average weekly working hours for Permit B holders are around 39.8 hours, which is roughly 3 hours more than Swiss residents. Permit C holders average around 39 hours per week, about 2.2 hours more than Swiss residents.

Permit B employees often have shorter or fixed-term contracts and must frequently apply for renewals, indicating a motivation to maintain stable employment. Permit C holders, on the other hand, may aim to obtain Swiss citizenship in the future, motivating them to work consistently and demonstrate their value to the country, especially given the complex interview and verification process for naturalization.
